## Conclusion
On average (10 iterations), I could get combined results of all records within 274 ms compared to 35714 ms, so the workaround on my given dataset is actually ~ 130 times faster.

I repeated the test for CouchDB 2 as well ([couchdb2-test-output](https://github.com/apache/couchdb/files/7038776/output2.txt)) and got an average of 447 ms with the new approach compared to 6917 ms which is still more than 15 times faster. So independent on the question if we should migrate to CouchDB 3 or not, it might still be a useful optimization also for CouchDB 2 setups.

